#Terminal node is the node which doesnt have any OUTGOING edge 
#Safe node is the one that gets started and eventually reaches to Terminal node 
EXAMPLE- 
0 -> 1 -> 2
          |
          v
        Terminal
Here:
2 is safe (terminal)
1 is safe (goes to 2)
0 is safe (goes to 1 → 2)

##MAIN IDEA
We reverse the gaph, so that we tell backward the node that they are safe. Like 2 is safe to tell 1 u r safe we move backward so we just
rverse the graph. And indegree in reverse is SAME as outgoing in normal graph. 

The logic is:
Reverse the graph.
Find all terminal nodes (outdegree = 0 in original graph). & (indegree in the revse graph)
Put them in queue.
Process parents.
Whatever gets processed is safe.

class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> eventualSafeNodes(int V, vector<int> adj[]) {

        vector<int> revAdj[V];
        vector<int> indegree(V, 0);

        // Reverse the graph
        for(int u = 0; u < V; u++) {
            for(auto v : adj[u]) {
                revAdj[v].push_back(u);
                indegree[u]++;   // original outdegree
            }
        }

        queue<int> q;

        // Terminal nodes
        for(int i = 0; i < V; i++) {
            if(indegree[i] == 0)
                q.push(i);
        }

        vector<int> ans;

        while(!q.empty()) {
            int node = q.front();
            q.pop();

            ans.push_back(node);

            for(auto parent : revAdj[node]) {
                indegree[parent]--;

                if(indegree[parent] == 0)
                    q.push(parent);
            }
        }

        sort(ans.begin(), ans.end());

        return ans;
    }
};
